Working at Rackspace, clouds are something that I think about a lot. Over the last year I've been working with the Microsoft Private Cloud. When I first went through the process of deploying an environment, it took about a week and a copious amount of swearing for the installation and integration of the System Center 2012 R2 components. To do a multitude of these deployments by hand would take a ridiculous amount of time and even more swearing. Luckily, Rob Willis, from Microsoft, wrote a powerful workflow called PowerShell Deployment Toolkit (PDT). PDT is a collection of PowerShell workflows and scripts bound together to achieve a single, glorious purpose, the deployment of System Center 2012 R2. At the time of this writing, the current version is 2.64.2611 and can be found [here](http://gallery.technet.microsoft.com/PowerShell-Deployment-f20bb605).

<!-- more -->

I first want to spend some time talking about the individual scripts and how they work. Then I'll show the steps to initiate the scripts to deploy your own test Microsoft Private Cloud.

**Downloader.ps1**

After extracting the zip file from the TechNet Gallery, you'll find a folder with all the good stuff in it. We'll start with the Downloader.ps1 file. The sole purpose of this file is to download all of the required installation media to build the Microsoft Private Cloud. With the release of Windows and System Center 2012 R2, you have to download the Windows Server ISOs and System Center 2012 R2 installers manually. The System Center installers can be found at [microsoft technet](http://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/evalcenter/dn205295.aspx).

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)



**Variables.xml / VariablesAD.xml**

After you have all the files downloaded it's time to tell PDT what to do with them. You can customize the architecture to be deployed via this file. The Installer and VMCreator PowerShell files read the values stored within this file to figure out what to do. You state the number of virtual machines that are deployed, and which roles are deployed on the servers. These roles include the various System Center components, Active Directory, SQL Server, WSUS, and the Windows Azure Pack. The Variables.xml can be a little intimidating given that it weighs in at a little over 400 lines. But once you get your hands dirty and dig into it you'll see that it's laid out very well and you'll be comfortable making edits to it in no time. If you elect to use an existing domain controller, you can remove Variables.xml and rename VariablesAD.xml to Variables.xml. Regardless of the route you take, the domain and local credentials are specified, and the virtual machines are joined to the domain listed in the file.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)



**VMCreator.ps1**

Another apply named file, this is the PowerShell script that will build the virtual machines on a Hyper-V Server. If you specified the default Variables.xml file, the script will mount the DC01 VHDX and copy the installation files as well as the Installer.ps1 file directly to the file system within the VHDX. Once the file transfer is complete, the script will power on the DC01 server, and complete the sysprep process and create the specified domain. After the domain is built, the VMCreator will power on all of the additional virtual machines that were provisioned, and the script ends its process. If the VariablesAD.xml file is chosen, the files are uploaded to the first virtual machine created, but the script will power on all of the virtual machines. Once all of the virtual machines are responding to pings and showing up in DNS, the Installer.ps1 script is automatically started up.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)



**Installer.ps1**

This PowerShell script runs on the domain controller created within the file or the first virtual machine in the list depending on which Variables file is used. The Installer file uses the Workflow.xml file to know the proper path and options to install the roles, and in which order is required. The script also creates folders for the logging of success or failures within the installation process.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)



**Workflow.xml**

If you thought Variable.xml was big, wait until you see Workflow.xml This beast of a XML file has over 34,000 lines and contains all of the workflow data that PowerShell uses in the installation and verification process. This file will check the version of the installers to make sure the build is consistent and supported with each deployment.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)





PDT is flexible enough to install System Center on a single Hyper-V server, or a whole farm of them, whichever is right for your situation. If you have a machine running Hyper-V, with at least 32GB of RAM, you can adjust the Variables file to use the bare minimum resources for these steps. If you have multiple Hyper-V servers you can have PDT spread out the roles on different servers to get the best performance or just to impress your coworkers.

Now with a better understanding on the function of individual files, here are the steps to build your own Microsoft Private Cloud:

Step 1) Download the Windows Server 2012 R2 ISO trial from [Microsoft](http://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/evalcenter/dn205286.aspx).

Step 2) Download Convert-WindowsImage.ps1 from [here](http://gallery.technet.microsoft.com/scriptcenter/Convert-WindowsImageps1-0fe23a8f)

- Run the PowerShell script to convert the ISO into a VHDX. Here is a sample command to use:
```powershell
\Convert-WindowsImage.ps1 -SourcePath "C:\Images\Windows2012R2.ISO" -VHDFormat VHDX -Edition ServerStandard -VHDPartitionStyle GPT -RemoteDesktopEnable
```

Step 3) Download the System Center 2012 R2 trial from Microsoft from the link above.

Step 4) Create the following directory structure on the server and copy the all of the images to the respective folders:

- App Controller -> `C:\Installer\Download\SystemCenter2012R2\AppController`
- Configuration Manager -> `C:\Installer\Download\SystemCenter2012R2\ConfigurationManager`
- Data Protection Manager -> `C:\Installer\Download\SystemCenter2012R2\DataProtectionManager`
- Operations Manager -> `C:\Installer\Download\SystemCenter2012R2\OperationsManager.en`
- Orchestrator -> `C:\Installer\Download\SystemCenter2012R2\Orchestrator`
- Service Manager -> `C:\Installer\Download\SystemCenter2012R2\ServiceManager`
- Virtual Machine Manager -> `C:\Installer\Download\SystemCenter2012R2\VirtualMachineManager`
- Windows Server 2012 R2 -> `C:\Installer\Download\WindowsServer2012R2`

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)



Step 5) Run `Downloader.ps1`

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)



Step 6) Once the files are downloaded and extracted, proceed to run `VMcreator.ps1`

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)



Step 7) After the VMCreator is complete, the `Installer.ps1` file is automatically ran. Depending on the specs of your Hyper-V server, this can take a few hours, so fire up some He-Man cartoons on Netflix and get comfortable. Once it's complete, you will have a fully functional Microsoft Private Cloud that you'll be proud to show off to your friends and coworkers
